Supplier in Java

Supplier is a functional interface that does not take any input but returns a value.

👉 Think of it as:
“give me something”

Syntax
Supplier<T>

👉 where T — тип возвращаемого значения

Basic Example
import java.util.function.Supplier;

Supplier<String> supplier = () -> "Hello";

System.out.println(supplier.get()); // Hello
Main Method
get()
T value = supplier.get();

👉 returns a value

Example with Random Values
Supplier<Double> random = () -> Math.random();

System.out.println(random.get());
Example with Object Creation
Supplier<List<String>> listSupplier = () -> new ArrayList<>();

List<String> list = listSupplier.get();
Real Use Cases
generating values
lazy initialization
creating objects
default values
Supplier vs Other Interfaces
Interface	Input	Output
Predicate	1	boolean
Function	1	value
Consumer	1	void
Supplier	0	value
Using Supplier with Optional
Optional<String> optional = Optional.empty();

String value = optional.orElseGet(() -> "Default value");

👉 value generated only if needed

Why use Supplier?
clean way to generate data
lazy execution
avoids unnecessary computations
Summary
Supplier → no input → returns value
main method: get()
used for generating data
useful for lazy logic
